            , of <placeName id="t18320216-254-crimeloc1449">Ratcliff-highway</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18320216-254-crimeloc1449" type="placeName" value="Ratcliff-highway"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18320216-254-crimeloc1449" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320216-254-off1447 t18320216-254-crimeloc1449"></join>. This cloak was lost from his shop, but I did not see it taken; I heard Stop thief! called, went to the door, and missed it - I did not see the prisoner that night, but a few days after Brown gave me notice that he was at the window, and I took him- the cloak has not been found.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320216-254-person2130">
                  JOHN 
                  BROWN
               <interp inst="t18320216-254-person2130" type="surname" value="BROWN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320216-254-person2130" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320216-254-person2130" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live close by the prosecutor's shop. -I saw the prisoner about half-past seven o'clock on the night of the 19th of January; he walked up and down the door two or three times, he then went on the step, took the cloak, and ran up Cannon-street - I cried out Stop thief! and the alarm was given, but he made his escape - this was on Thursday, between seven and eight o'clock, and on the Tuesday after I saw him again looking in at the window; I went and told Mr. Cousins the man was outside the door, and he was taken: I know the prisoner was the man that took the cloak - it was dark, but he had<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183202160092"></xptr>passed me three or four times, and looked at me - I saw him for five minutes.</p>
               <p>MR. COUSINS. Brown gave a very clear description of the prisoner the same night, and it exactly corresponded with his person.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. He said at the office that he only knew me by my coat and hat, but, having two or three hearings, he spoke more confidently of me.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18320216-254-verdict1450" type="verdictDescription">
